Machine Learning Based Survival Prediction in Non-metastatic Triple Negative Breast Cancer Using SEER Database

BMIN503/EPID600 Final Project

Author

Wenyuan(Vivian) Ye

Overview

This project aimed to provide population-based prognostic analysis in non-metastatic triple negative breast cancer(TNBC) patients using data extracted from the Surveillance, Epidemiology,and End Results (SEER) database. It first investigated the independent prognostic factors for patient overall survival(OS). Then it constructed and validated prediction models for patient prognosis using machine learning, and presented a comparative analysis of four different models, Logistic Regression(LR), Decision Tree(DF), Random Forest(RF), and Gradient Boosting Machine(GBM). The findings of the project provided a tool to predict survival outcomes of patients with non-metastatic TNBC and contributed to the improvement of individualized treatment and long-term follow-up for these patients. Link to my final project GitHub Repo

Introduction

Breast cancer(BC) is the second most commonlyÂ diagnosed cancer in women in the United States, excluding skin cancers [1]. Moreover, it is the primary cause of death among women worldwide [2]. The death rate of BC in the U.S. hasÂ been decreasing steadily since 1989,Â owing to the early detection and enhanced awareness, along with advanced treatments. However, this decline has shown a slight decrease in recent years [3]. TNBC is a typeÂ of breast cancer characterized by negative estrogen receptor, progesterone receptor, and human epidermal growth factor receptor. TNBC generally exhibits more aggressive behavior, a higher likelihood of recurrence, and a worse prognosis [4]. Recurrence-free survival(RFS) and overall survival(OS) rates are both low for TNBC patients, as they are resistant to endocrine therapy and molecular-targeted therapy, and most rely on chemotherapy [5]. Identifying non-metastatic TNBC patients who remain at high risk of death has been a primary focus of researchers attempting to curtail TNBC mortality. The predictive analysis of TNBC patients can provide reference for evaluating clinical patients to determine surgical methods and develop adjuvant therapies, as well as support the development of individualized treatment plans.

With the advent of the big data era, professional medical information has been integrated into large datasets, fostering the integration of machine learning methods within the medical industry. Presently, machine learning has been served as a valuable tool for analyzing complex datasets and predicting risks and survival rates for cancer patients, resulting in a significant increase in accuracy rates [6]. However, machine learning algorithms have some limitations that require practical improvement. For instance, support vector machines (SVM) struggle with processing large numbers samples and variables, K-nearest neighbors (KNN) are not easily interpretable, and decision trees (DF) are quick to train yet not adequately complex [7]. Conversely, Gradient Boosting Machine (GBM) is developed iteratively to achieve loss-function minimization, which allows for superior performance in various fields [8-10]. Nevertheless, it is rarely applied to clinical patient prognosis prediction. Few studies have been conducted using machine learning to study TNBC prognosis, and few prediction models have been compared and validated. Therefore, a more accurate and powerful prognosis prediction model based on machine learning is needed for TNBC patients.

Methods

Data source and patient selection

The Surveillance, Epidemiology, and End Results (SEER) database is one of the most comprehensive and complete large-scale tumor registries in North America, gathering a vast quantity of evidence-based and medicine related data with an approximate coverage of one-third of the U.S. population [11]. In this study, I used SEER*Stat version 8.4.2 to generate a case list. I enrolled patients according to the following inclusion criteria: female; year of diagnosis from 2010 to 2020; breast carcinoma as the only primary malignant cancer diagnosis; American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) 7th edition stage I-III; triple negative subtype. Patients who present with distant metastasis, in situ disease, unknownÂ race, unknown tumor stage and unknown laterality were expelled from this study. Patient sociodemographic and clinicalÂ characteristics were gathered, including age, race, marital status, surgery status, chemotherapy status,Â radiotherapy status, survivalÂ time, cause of death, year of death,Â and months from diagnosis to treatment. Tumor characteristics were also collected, including grade, laterality, AJCC stage, histologic type, tumor size and nodal status.Â Enrolled patients were followed up until death, loss to follow-up or December 31, 2020.

Some information in the raw database was not related to this study. Therefore, the database was cleaned for better use. The age of selected patients was divided into six categories(<40, 40-49, 50-59, 60-69, 70-79, and >=80 years old). Race was categorized separately as white, black, and other races. Marital status was classified separately as married, singled, divorced/widowed/other, and unknown. Moreover, the months from diagnosis to treatment was divided into two categories: 0 month, and >=1 month.

dataset$Age = case_match(dataset$Age, 
  c("20-24","25-29","30-34","35-39") ~ "<40",
  c("40-44","45-49") ~ "40-49",
  c("50-54","55-59") ~ "50-59",
  c("60-64","65-69") ~ "60-69",
  c("70-74","75-79") ~ "70-79",
  c("80-84","85+")  ~ ">=80" ) 
dataset$Race = case_match(dataset$Race, 
  "White" ~ "White",
  "Black" ~ "Black",
  c("American Indian/Alaska Native","Asian or Pacific Islander") ~ "Other") 
dataset$'Marital status at diagnosis' = case_match(dataset$'Marital status at diagnosis', 
  c("Divorced","Widowed","Separated","Unmarried or Domestic Partner") ~ "Divorced/widowed/other",
  "Single (never married)" ~ "Singled",
  "Married (including common law)" ~ "Married",
  "Unknown" ~ "Unknown") 
dataset$Radiation = case_match(dataset$Radiation, 
  c("Beam radiation","Combination of beam with implants or isotopes","Radiation, NOS  method or source not specified","Radioactive implants (includes brachytherapy) (1988+)","Radioisotopes (1988+)") ~ "Yes",
  c("Refused (1988+)","None/Unknown","Recommended, unknown if administered") ~ "No/Unknown")    
dataset$'AJCC Stage Group' = case_match(dataset$'AJCC Stage Group', 
  c("IA","IB") ~ "I",
  c("IIA","IIB") ~ "II",
  c("III","IIIA","IIIB","IIIC","IIINOS") ~ "III" ) 
dataset$Surgery = case_match(dataset$Surgery,
  0:19 ~ "No/unknown",
  20:90  ~ "Yes" )
dataset$Grade = case_match(dataset$Grade, 
  "Well differentiated; Grade I" ~ "I",
  "Moderately differentiated; Grade II" ~ "II",
  "Poorly differentiated; Grade III" ~ "III",
  "Undifferentiated; anaplastic; Grade IV" ~ "IV",
  "Unknown" ~ "Unknown") 
dataset$'AJCC T Stage' = case_match(dataset$'AJCC T Stage', 
  c("T1","T1a","T1b","T1c","T1mic") ~ "T1",
  c("T4","T4a","T4b","T4c","T4d") ~ "T4",
  "T0" ~ "T0",
  "T2" ~ "T2",
  "T3" ~ "T3") 
dataset$'AJCC N Stage' = case_match(dataset$'AJCC N Stage', 
  c("N1","N1a","N1b","N1c","N1mi") ~ "N1",
  c("N2","N2a","N2b","N2NOS") ~ "N2",
  c("N3","N3a","N3b","N3c","N3NOS") ~ "N3",
  "N0" ~ "N0" ) 
dataset$'Months from diagnosis to treatment' <- as.numeric(dataset$'Months from diagnosis to treatment')|> case_match(
 0 ~ "0 month",
 1:18 ~ ">=1 month")

A new column of patient survival status named âSurvivalStatusâ was created based on the column of âYear of death recodeâ. The label of âcensoredâ means that patient is alive at last contact. Two new columns of patient 3-year OS status named âOS_3yearâ and 5-year OS status named âOS_5yearâ were created based on the columns of âSurvival monthsâ and âCOD to site recodeâ(a recode based on underlying cause of death). Columns related to the study were selected to facilitate further use.

dataset.BC <- dataset |> 
  mutate(
  SurvivalStatus = ifelse(dataset$'Year of death recode' == "Alive at last contact","censored","dead"),
   OS_3year = case_when((dataset$'Survival months' < 36 & dataset$'COD to site recode' != "Alive") ~ "dead",
                      .default = "censored"),
   OS_5year = case_when((dataset$'Survival months' < 60 & dataset$'COD to site recode' != "Alive") ~ "dead",
                      .default = "censored")
       )|>
  select(Age,Sex,'Marital status at diagnosis',Race,Radiation,Chemotherapy,Surgery,'Histologic Type','Laterality',Grade,'AJCC Stage Group','AJCC T Stage','AJCC N Stage','Survival months','Months from diagnosis to treatment',SurvivalStatus,OS_5year,OS_3year) |>
  mutate_if(is.character,as.factor)

Results

Patient characteristics

The summary of both sociodemographic and clinical characteristics of selected patients was shown in TableÂ 1 . Overall, a total of 5,058 eligible patients with a diagnosis of non-metastatic TNBC were enrolled in this study. The histological distribution of enrolled patients was: invasive ductal carcinoma(IDC)Â 4,304 (85%), invasive lobular carcinoma(ILC) 123 (2.4%), mixed invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma (IDLC) 101 (2.0%), and other typesÂ 531 (10%). At the end of follow-up, 2,124 (42%)Â ofÂ total patients received radiation, 3,658 (72%) received chemotherapy, and 4,674 (92%)Â received surgery of primary tumor. The median survival time was 41 months. The 3-year OS rate for total patients was 78%, and the 5-year OS rate was 71%.

We could see in FigureÂ 1 that higher positive correlations existed between survival status(both 3-year and 5-year) and AJCC stage group, AJCC T stage, as well as AJCC N stage.

Univariate and multivariate analyses of the risk factors of OS

Cox univariate survival analysis was performed for each variable to analyze the relationship between various clinical and pathological characteristics and patient survival status. As demonstrated in TableÂ 2 , the Cox univariate regression results differentiated twelve variables (age, race, marital status, surgery, chemotherapy, radiation, AJCC stage group, AJCC T stage, AJCC N stage, histologic type, grade, and months from diagnosis to treatment) that were significantly associated with survival time (P<0.05).

#change the reference category in regression
dataset.BC2$Marital_status_at_diagnosis = factor(dataset.BC2$Marital_status_at_diagnosis, levels = c("Married", "Divorced/widowed/other", "Singled", "Unknown")) 
dataset.BC2$Race = factor(dataset.BC2$Race, levels = c("White", "Black", "Other"))

dataset.BC2  |> 
    select(Survival_months, Age, Marital_status_at_diagnosis,Race,Radiation,Chemotherapy,Surgery,AJCC_Stage_Group,Histologic_Type,Laterality,Grade,AJCC_T_Stage,AJCC_N_Stage,Months_from_diagnosis_to_treatment,SurvivalStatus) |>
  tbl_uvregression(
    method = coxph,
    y = Surv(time = Survival_months, event = SurvivalStatus == 'dead'),
    exponentiate = TRUE,
    pvalue_fun = ~style_pvalue(.x, digits = 3) ) |> 
  bold_labels() |> 
  as_gt()

These variables were then included in the multivariate Cox regression model. It should be noted that AJCC stage group corresponds to the AJCC T stage and N stage of tumor stage categorization. Therefore, only AJCC T stage and N stage classifications were included in the multivariate analysis. Based on the results of multivariate analysis in TableÂ 3 , I found eight variables, including age â¥70 years (P <0.001), white race(vs.Â other races) (P =0.006), higher T stage (P <0.001), higher N stage (P <0.001), no/unknown surgery (P <0.001), no/unknown radiation (P <0.001), no/unknown chemotherapy (P <0.001), and 0 month from diagnosis to treatment (P = 0.023), were independent risk variables in the poor prognosis of non-metastatic TNBC patients. The forest plot illustrated the results of multivariable Cox regression analysis of these independent risk variables.

mveregression <- 
  coxph(Surv(time = Survival_months, 
             event = SurvivalStatus == 'dead') ~ Age + Race + Radiation + Chemotherapy + Surgery + Marital_status_at_diagnosis + Histologic_Type + AJCC_T_Stage + AJCC_N_Stage + Grade + Months_from_diagnosis_to_treatment, 
             data = dataset.BC2)
tbl_regression(mveregression, exponentiate = TRUE) |>
  bold_labels() |> 
  as_gt()

KaplanâMeier survival curves of the risk factors of OS

Furthermore, to accurately estimate the survival probability in different patient subgroups with different potential risk factors, I used the eight variables (p < 0.05) obtained from the multivariate Cox regression model above to plot the KaplanâMeier survival curves. As shown in K-M survival curves, age (P < 0.0001), race (P = 0.022), radiation (P = 0.00034), chemotherapy (P < 0.0001), surgery (P < 0.0001), AJCC T stage (P < 0.0001), AJCC N stage (P < 0.0001), and <1 month from diagnosis to treatment (P = 0.0043) were all significantly associated with the cumulative survival probability. However, a paradoxical effect was observed for patient groups with different time from diagnosis to treatment: survival was better in patients with longer time to treatment(>= 1 month), suggesting a complex association between time to treatment and survival. This association was probably confounded by unmeasured patients, tumor-specific factors, or hospital-related factors. In addition, patients with more advanced diseases presenting with severe signs and symptoms seem to receive treatment more promptly compared with fitter patients.

Predictive models construction and validation

Before building machine learning models, all patients were randomly divided into 2 sets, a training set and a testing set, at a 8:2 ratio. 10-fold cross validation classification sets were obtained for model development.Â 

dataset.BC3 <- dataset.BC2 |> 
  mutate(
  Age70 = as.factor(case_when((dataset.BC2$Age %in% c("<40","40-49","50-59","60-69"))~ "<70",
                              (dataset.BC2$Age %in% c("70-79",">=80")) ~ ">=70"))
          )

set.seed(1234)
dataset.BC.split <- initial_split(dataset.BC3, 
                            strata = SurvivalStatus, 
                            prop = 0.80)
dataset.BC.train <- training(dataset.BC.split)
dataset.BC.test <- testing(dataset.BC.split)
dataset.training.folds <- vfold_cv(dataset.BC.train, v = 10)

Based on the results of multivariate analysis and KM survival curves, seven variables, including age, race, radiation, chemotherapy, surgery, AJCC T stage, and AJCC N stage, were screened out to establish prognosis models. Logistic Regression (LR), Decision Tree (DT), Random Forest (RF), and Gradient Boosting Machine (GBM) models were developed to predict the 3-year and 5-year OS. 10-fold cross-validations were used to prevent overfitting. Receiver operating characteristic (ROC) analysis was used for the evaluation of the performances of these models. For LR, DT, and RF models, the values of area under the ROC curve (AUC) and accuracy were calculated for both cross-validations and testing set. For the GBM regression model, Mean Squared Error (MSE), Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) and AUC value were used as the evaluation metrics. The importance of each predictor was evaluated individually by ranking each predictor based on some univariate metrics, and then selecting the top-ranking predictors.

For the GBM model, 10-fold cross-validations on the training set were used to assess the optimal number of subtrees. As shown in the figure below, the logarithmic loss function was minimized at a number of 376. From this, the ân.treesâ parameter was determined, and the model was then iteratively tested and adjusted through grid search to confirm other main hyperparameters to obtain the best model. The iteration process was simplified in the following code chunk.

set.seed(123) 
gbm1 <- gbm(
  formula = OS_3year ~ Age70 + Race + Radiation + Chemotherapy + Surgery + AJCC_T_Stage + AJCC_N_Stage,
  data = dataset.BC3,
  distribution = "gaussian",  # SSE loss function
  n.trees = 700,
  shrinkage = 0.01,
  interaction.depth = 10,
  n.minobsinnode = 15,
  cv.folds = 10
)
gbm.perf(gbm1, method = "cv")# 10-fold cross-validation in the train set to determine the optimal number of subtrees

[1] 376
hyper_grid <- expand.grid(     # create hyperparameter grid
  shrinkage = c(.05, .1, .15),
  interaction.depth = c(13, 15, 17),
  n.minobsinnode = c(20, 23, 26),          
  min_RMSE = 0                 # a place to dump results
)
# train model
for(i in 1:nrow(hyper_grid)) { 
  set.seed(123)  
  gbm.tune <- gbm(
    formula = OS_3year ~ Age70 + Race + Radiation + Chemotherapy + Surgery + AJCC_T_Stage + AJCC_N_Stage,
    distribution = "gaussian",
    data = dataset.BC3,
    n.trees = 376,
    interaction.depth = hyper_grid$interaction.depth[i],
    shrinkage = hyper_grid$shrinkage[i],
    n.minobsinnode = hyper_grid$n.minobsinnode[i],
    cv.folds = 10,
    train.fraction = .8,
    n.cores = NULL,   # will use all cores by default
    verbose = FALSE
  )
  hyper_grid$min_RMSE[i] <- sqrt(min(gbm.tune$valid.error))  # add min training error and trees to grid
}

hyper_grid %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(min_RMSE) %>%
  head(6)           # present the top model with its main parameters
  shrinkage interaction.depth n.minobsinnode  min_RMSE

Discussion and Conclusion

In this study, I examined the independent prognostic factors for OS in non-metastatic TNBC women, and developed and validated machine learning models to predict TNBC prognosis. The analysis identified seven variables,Â includingÂ age, race, radiation, chemotherapy, surgery, AJCC T stage, and AJCC N stage, as independent prognostic factorsÂ inÂ predicting long-term OS in non-metastatic TNBC patients. Based on these variables, I successfully establishedÂ four prognosis models, LR, DF, RF, and GBM, for predicting 3- and 5- year OS in selected patient cohort using 10-fold cross-validations. Results showed that GBM outperformed the other models, attaining an AUC of 0.809 for predicting 3-year survival, and an AUC of 0.788 for predicting 5-year survival. The results of this study provide evidence indicating that the GBM model is a reliable and efficacious tool for predicting long-term survival in TNBC patients. The findings could also help clinicians better distinguish high-risk TNBC patients and devise better-individualized management plans, including relatively more aggressive treatment approaches.

In addition to the models described in the main body, Kaplan-Meier survival curves were constructed for different patient subgroupsÂ divided by potential risk factors. Patients who underwent radiation, chemotherapy, or surgery demonstrated a superior response to prolonged survival in comparison to those who did not undergo these treatments. The importance scores of each variableÂ showed thatÂ AJCC T and N features derived from the AJCC staging exhibitedÂ the greatest impact in predicting survival outcomes. Since AJCC T stage indicates the size of the primary tumor and AJCC N stage indicates the number of lymph nodes impacted by cancer, both of which correlate with tumor burden, a higher AJCCÂ T or N stage typically means higher tumor burden, leading to an increased risk of decreased survival time.

However, it is important to acknowledge some inevitable limitations in this study. First, the character of the retrospective design was inevitably flawed with bias. Second, the SEER database only provided OS, so we could not estimate cancer-specific survival time nor eliminate the impact of comorbidity on patient outcomes. Although breast cancer is a leading cause of death in this patient cohort, the presence of different comorbidities might lead to potential bias, particularly if not measured accurately. Therefore, it is crucial to evaluate the benefits and drawbacks of prediction model options on a case-by-case basis. Third, some clinical risk factors (e.g., Ki-67 index, 21-Gene Recurrence Score, BRCA1- and BRCA2- related mutation)[12-14], and information on insurance and socioeconomic status[15,16] that have been found to be associated with the young breast cancer-specific survival in other studies were unavailable in the SEER database. Finally, it should be noted that the models created in this study have yet to be confirmed in the external validation cohort. In conclusion, further research is needed to accurately isolate the various contributing factors and explore how machine learning incorporates the inherent complexity of clinical decision-making, as well as its impact on patient outcomes.
